result.execSummary:
The defendant Mauricio Garcia Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Strangulation and Suffocation [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse - Infliction of Physical Pain or Injury, Repeater], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.235(1).
  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse - Infliction of Physical Pain or Injury, Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

case called at 3:48pm. [MK]
Defendant Mauricio  Garcia in court with Attorney Sylvie Dahnert.  ADA Brookellen Teuber appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights given; plea of " Guilty " entered on Counts #1 & #2; factual basis stipulated including as to the Repeater status; victim rights compliance verified (ADA Teuber submits the victim impact statement; the victim is present); the Court accepts the pleas, finds Mr. Garcia guilty of Counts #1 & #2, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #3 and #4; further, the Court reads-in uncharged referrals for Bailjumping: DA Case #14JE1249, with dates of violation between June 8 through June 30, 2014 involving ongoing contact with the victim C.G., and the Court bars further prosecution of these referrals.

On Counts #1 and #2, the Court withholds sentence, and places Mr. Garcia on Probation for three years, with conditions:

--on Count #1: to serve 90 days in the Jefferson County Jail, to commence forthwith
--the Court gives the work-release warning language regarding the requirement to report and serve without non-prescribed controlled substances and alcohol in his system. After Mr. Garcia indicates that he will test positive today, the Court indicates to Mr. Garcia that if he wishes to have work-release privileges, he is to submit a request for this to the Court for its consideration
--the Court authorizes transfer of the service of this jail term to the Walworth County Jail conditional on there being no use of electronic monitoring 
--contact with Chelsey Garcia only as approved by Ms. Garcia and by the Supervising Agent; an exception to this condition is to be present in the courtroom for court proceedings 
--no acts or threats of violence toward anyone
--to successfully complete a Certified Batterers Treatment Group Program; this is to commence within the first six months of the Probation term
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, and counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to obtain/maintain fulltime employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--on Count #1: to comply with DNA sample provision
--on Count #1: to pay costs of $268 plus $63 subpoena fees, plus $100 domestic abuse surcharge, plus $250 DNA surcharge
--on Count #2: to pay costs of $243, plus $100 domestic abuse surcharge, plus $200 DNA surcharge
--to reimburse Jefferson County for court-appointed attorney fees 

Days credit for time already served:  3 days
Felony firearm and voting warnings/penalties given
Contact prohibition warnings/penalties given

case called at 9:21am. 
Defendant Mauricio Garcia in court.  ADA Monica Hall appears for the State of Wisconsin.
This case is scheduled for Preliminary Hearing today, however Mr. Garcia indicates that he intended to have counsel at this hearing. 
Mr. Garcia indicates that, when he was in the Jefferson County Jail at the time of arrest and his initial court appearance, Mr. Garcia was found to not be eligible for PD counsel, and that he completed the Petition-form for the court-appointment of counsel. He reports that he turned the Petition for the appointment of counsel into the jail social worker.
The Court indicates to Mr. Garcia that the case file does not include the PD non-eligibility document or the petition-form.  
The Court adjourns, but indicates that it intends to reschedule the hearing in approximately three weeks, so Mr. Garcia needs to go to the PD Office today to obtain the eligibility determination and, if he does not qualify, to return to the Clerk of Courts Office to file the petition-form.
ADA Hall notes that an officer-witness is present and the State was ready to proceed to Preliminary Hearing today. 
ADA Hall indicates that the State is now waiving Preliminary Hearing time limits.
Mr. Garcia verifies that the 508 E. North Street address remains current.
recess 9:25am.
